1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,600
 - Hello, welcome to chapter three.

2
00:00:01,600 --> 00:00:04,380
 I'm Charles Severance, and I'm your instructor.

3
00:00:04,380 --> 00:00:07,360
 So here in chapter three, again, I want you to read the book.

4
00:00:07,360 --> 00:00:10,560
 I'm just gonna call your attention to a few of the

5
00:00:10,560 --> 00:00:14,960
 unique things that might help you make more sense of the book.

6
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,720
 So we're gonna talk about semicolon use,

7
00:00:17,720 --> 00:00:21,080
 how it started in C and is used across multiple languages,

8
00:00:21,080 --> 00:00:24,400
 how else if is a little different across languages,

9
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:26,120
 the switch statement and a bit of motivation

10
00:00:26,120 --> 00:00:28,840
 why the switch statement is even in C,

11
00:00:28,840 --> 00:00:32,640
 is a comma, I don't know, operator, separator,

12
00:00:32,640 --> 00:00:37,440
 and then sort of this tendency towards excessive succinctness

13
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:41,600
 or brevity that is pretty common in C programming, right?

14
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:45,720
 It just, it's like there's such a value

15
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:47,320
 in making things really, really short,

16
00:00:47,320 --> 00:00:49,840
 and that makes it kind of different.

17
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:52,760
 So I love semicolon-based languages,

18
00:00:52,760 --> 00:00:57,080
 and we have a whole bunch of semicolon-based languages

19
00:00:57,080 --> 00:01:00,880
 that we've learned and are going to learn.

20
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:04,480
 Certainly 1978, the C programming language

21
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:08,320
 with its non-syntactically important spacing.

22
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:13,200
 The key to C is that C, the semicolon, is a terminator,

23
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:17,120
 and every statement must be terminated by a semicolon.

24
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:19,520
 So we say x equals x plus one semicolon,

25
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:22,000
 and x equals x divided by two semicolon, right?

26
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,120
 And that's the idea, the printf ends in a semicolon.

27
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:27,920
 So you may or may not know, in Python,

28
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:30,400
 you're allowed to have semicolons.

29
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:32,360
 They're pretty much optional,

30
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:34,720
 like on the print open paren x closed paren,

31
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,040
 that semicolon does not need to be there.

32
00:01:37,040 --> 00:01:39,960
 But it is a separator, not a terminator.

33
00:01:39,960 --> 00:01:41,920
 So you can think of the print open paren x

34
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:45,640
 closed paren semicolon as one statement

35
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:48,160
 followed by a separator followed by an empty statement,

36
00:01:48,160 --> 00:01:49,720
 which does nothing.

37
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:52,080
 But the interesting thing is you can put

38
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:55,360
 more than one line on one line.

39
00:01:55,360 --> 00:01:56,960
 You can put more than one line of code

40
00:01:56,960 --> 00:01:58,240
 by using a separator.

41
00:01:58,240 --> 00:02:01,200
 So there I say x equals x plus one semicolon,

42
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:03,600
 x equals x over two semicolon.

43
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:04,960
 I don't have to indent that.

44
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:09,800
 I just, it's two lines in the same block of code,

45
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:11,720
 and that's legal.

46
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:15,440
 Most of the time, people choose not to use semicolon.

47
00:02:15,440 --> 00:02:18,560
 The other thing about that is that shell scripting,

48
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:21,840
 which is sort of the Linux automation,

49
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:22,920
 treats it as a separator.

50
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:25,120
 And so that sort of looks a bit like shell scripting

51
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:28,520
 to have multiple statements on the same line

52
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:30,520
 separated by semicolons.

53
00:02:30,520 --> 00:02:34,600
 In Java, it tends to follow the C pattern

54
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:36,460
 where it's a terminator.

55
00:02:36,460 --> 00:02:38,320
 I tend to like it as a terminator.

56
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:40,920
 I don't like the idea that you can leave it off

57
00:02:40,920 --> 00:02:42,160
 the way JavaScript does.

58
00:02:42,160 --> 00:02:45,120
 And so you see it's on two assignment statements

59
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,680
 and the system out printlin in Java.

60
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:52,280
 In PHP, PHP follows C very closely.

61
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:56,600
 And so it is a terminator there as well.

62
00:02:56,600 --> 00:02:59,040
 And so I think that's natural.

63
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:00,800
 And the good news, if it's a separator,

64
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:03,160
 like in JavaScript in the next example,

65
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:05,320
 where it's separating it.

66
00:03:05,320 --> 00:03:08,740
 And so in this case, the x equals x divided by two

67
00:03:08,740 --> 00:03:10,400
 does not need to be terminated

68
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:14,320
 'cause the closed curly brace is gonna terminate that.

69
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:18,560
 And like even the console.log, open paren, closed paren,

70
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:21,720
 semicolon, that semicolon is optional.

71
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:23,320
 When I tend to write JavaScript,

72
00:03:23,320 --> 00:03:25,580
 I tend to put semicolons everywhere.

73
00:03:25,580 --> 00:03:29,560
 When I tend to write Python, I put semicolons nowhere.

74
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:31,740
 And then in PHP and Java,

75
00:03:31,740 --> 00:03:36,040
 I tend to put semicolons everywhere.

76
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:39,200
 Even though sometimes there are things you can leave out.

77
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:42,340
 Another thing that is very, very subtle

78
00:03:42,340 --> 00:03:45,680
 is the notion of else if.

79
00:03:45,680 --> 00:03:48,120
 So C predates Python.

80
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:53,120
 And C in this book shows else if

81
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:54,560
 as two separate words.

82
00:03:54,560 --> 00:03:57,800
 And there's an else keyword and an if keyword.

83
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:00,080
 And so you say else space if.

84
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:02,920
 And then you have the expression and another statement.

85
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:05,300
 Else space if expression and another statement.

86
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:07,000
 And then else for the one

87
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,800
 where none of those expressions are true.

88
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:12,520
 And if you look at Python, it looks almost identical.

89
00:04:12,520 --> 00:04:16,640
 It says if expression, then elif expression,

90
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:18,320
 elif expression and else.

91
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:24,500
 The key is that elif is a separate language construct

92
00:04:24,500 --> 00:04:25,520
 in Python.

93
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:28,420
 And I think it's actually really beautiful and elegant.

94
00:04:28,420 --> 00:04:31,700
 And the key is that this else if,

95
00:04:31,700 --> 00:04:33,640
 while it is, I can think of it in C

96
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:36,400
 as like indented incorrectly.

97
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:39,380
 So you can look at it as the very first if

98
00:04:39,380 --> 00:04:41,880
 has an if and an else.

99
00:04:41,880 --> 00:04:44,120
 And everything from the second if on down

100
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:46,200
 is really part of that else.

101
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:48,080
 And so if you look to the right,

102
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:49,440
 you see the curly braces

103
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:51,460
 with the indentation that's explicit.

104
00:04:51,460 --> 00:04:53,360
 It's exactly the same thing.

105
00:04:53,360 --> 00:04:57,040
 But what you're going to see is you can see that it's,

106
00:04:57,040 --> 00:05:00,000
 if you were gonna truly correctly indent

107
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,380
 an if, else if, else if, else in C,

108
00:05:03,380 --> 00:05:06,120
 you would indent it the way it's shown on the right side.

109
00:05:06,120 --> 00:05:09,440
 And it's neither here nor there.

110
00:05:09,440 --> 00:05:11,440
 Very, very, it is very rare

111
00:05:11,440 --> 00:05:14,040
 that you would see any C programmer, you know,

112
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:16,400
 do all the indentation the technically right way.

113
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:18,460
 But I just want to call your attention to it

114
00:05:18,460 --> 00:05:20,160
 that it's different than eleph.

115
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:22,520
 Eleph is its own language element

116
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:24,400
 that is not a deeper nesting,

117
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:25,920
 deeper and deeper nesting.

118
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:26,760
 If you were to nest it,

119
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:28,040
 you see on the right hand side,

120
00:05:28,040 --> 00:05:31,080
 you see I've got three closed curly braces.

121
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:32,520
 Curly brace, curly brace, curly brace.

122
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:33,840
 And it's just, ugh.

123
00:05:33,840 --> 00:05:36,680
 So the eleph, I think, is a really elegant addition

124
00:05:36,680 --> 00:05:38,440
 that Python has added.

125
00:05:38,440 --> 00:05:40,740
 Thus, which statement?

126
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,020
 (sighs)

127
00:05:44,020 --> 00:05:46,080
 I think that the reason that the authors

128
00:05:46,080 --> 00:05:48,340
 put the switch statement into C

129
00:05:48,340 --> 00:05:52,320
 is there was a time where we would write code

130
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:55,760
 in assembly language using what we call a jump table,

131
00:05:55,760 --> 00:05:58,160
 where we take sort of the, take a number,

132
00:05:58,160 --> 00:06:01,720
 maybe take it, mask it so it's only from zero through 16,

133
00:06:01,720 --> 00:06:03,920
 and then look up a series of addresses

134
00:06:03,920 --> 00:06:06,000
 and jump through a jump table.

135
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,920
 And the computed go-to was the way in Fortran

136
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:11,400
 of expressing a jump table.

137
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:13,480
 But in Fortran, it was just a mess.

138
00:06:13,480 --> 00:06:17,160
 You got these labels and columns one through six,

139
00:06:17,160 --> 00:06:20,480
 and the continue statement doesn't work like the continuing

140
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:23,160
 in C and C-like languages.

141
00:06:23,160 --> 00:06:24,640
 And you had to have these go-tos

142
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:27,260
 to get out of the switch statement.

143
00:06:27,260 --> 00:06:28,160
 If you think about it

144
00:06:28,160 --> 00:06:29,920
 from an assembly language perspective,

145
00:06:29,920 --> 00:06:32,260
 it's not that hard to build the computed go-to

146
00:06:32,260 --> 00:06:34,040
 with a little tiny jump table.

147
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:37,640
 And so I think to some degree,

148
00:06:37,640 --> 00:06:40,720
 whether or not we have to use a jump table in modern C

149
00:06:40,720 --> 00:06:43,280
 is really, it's really, really rare

150
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:44,760
 where you have to use a jump table.

151
00:06:44,760 --> 00:06:48,660
 We just would do a few repeating LSIFs, and it's just fine.

152
00:06:48,660 --> 00:06:52,040
 Back then, a few extra statements might have bothered

153
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:54,520
 something if you were gonna do it a million times,

154
00:06:54,520 --> 00:06:57,180
 you know, a million times a minute or something.

155
00:06:57,180 --> 00:06:58,760
 The switch statement is much prettier.

156
00:06:58,760 --> 00:07:00,480
 You do have to put the break statements in there.

157
00:07:00,480 --> 00:07:03,400
 You can kind of nest the, you have the stack cases,

158
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:04,920
 and then there's a default case.

159
00:07:04,920 --> 00:07:08,320
 So if I, at least I compare the C switch statement

160
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:10,920
 with the Fortran computed go-to,

161
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:12,800
 I wanna say that the C switch statement

162
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,040
 was pretty much a lot more elegant,

163
00:07:15,040 --> 00:07:17,760
 a lot easier to use, a lot easier to understand.

164
00:07:17,760 --> 00:07:20,240
 And because assembly language programmers of the time

165
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:22,420
 did think in terms of jump tables,

166
00:07:22,420 --> 00:07:24,640
 if a high-level language didn't have a way

167
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:27,040
 to express a jump table in that language,

168
00:07:27,040 --> 00:07:30,200
 then we would kind of think of it as missing.

169
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:32,960
 But frankly, you know, in your programming,

170
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:36,160
 I'm not sure I've written a switch statement in,

171
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:37,640
 'cause Java has a switch statement too.

172
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:39,120
 I probably haven't written a switch statement

173
00:07:39,120 --> 00:07:42,360
 in over 20 years and maybe more.

174
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:45,920
 So I like the fact that it improved on Fortran,

175
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:48,080
 but that doesn't mean that you should use it.

176
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:52,600
 The comma operator or comma separator,

177
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:54,640
 I like to think of it as like a light version

178
00:07:54,640 --> 00:07:56,120
 of the semicolon.

179
00:07:56,120 --> 00:08:00,560
 And most people almost never use it,

180
00:08:00,560 --> 00:08:05,560
 and the only place we use it is when it is sort of idiomatic,

181
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,040
 where in a for statement,

182
00:08:08,040 --> 00:08:10,280
 because we're already using semicolon

183
00:08:10,280 --> 00:08:12,600
 to separate the start before the loop,

184
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:17,600
 the loop test, and then the loop increment per iteration,

185
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,240
 we're using semicolon for that.

186
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:21,940
 So if we wanna do like two statements,

187
00:08:21,940 --> 00:08:23,840
 we are gonna like, oh, i equals zero,

188
00:08:23,840 --> 00:08:26,320
 j equals strlen s minus one,

189
00:08:26,320 --> 00:08:27,480
 with a comma in between to say,

190
00:08:27,480 --> 00:08:30,200
 do these two things before the loop starts.

191
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:34,240
 And then at the end, you say i plus plus comma j minus minus,

192
00:08:34,240 --> 00:08:37,480
 that says do these two things at the end of each loop.

193
00:08:37,480 --> 00:08:41,400
 So I only see it in idiomatic situations.

194
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:44,860
 Just think of it as like we couldn't use a semicolon here.

195
00:08:44,860 --> 00:08:47,960
 It functions exactly like a semicolon,

196
00:08:47,960 --> 00:08:50,060
 although the syntax already has a semicolon in it.

197
00:08:50,060 --> 00:08:54,760
 So I think it's actually a pretty clever way to say,

198
00:08:54,760 --> 00:08:56,160
 I wanna put two statements in here.

199
00:08:56,160 --> 00:08:58,120
 Maybe you could put curly braces in there or something,

200
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:00,520
 but I thought the comma was a pretty cool thing.

201
00:09:02,120 --> 00:09:05,800
 Another problem is that there was just this notion

202
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:09,160
 that we, as assembly language programmers,

203
00:09:09,160 --> 00:09:10,920
 we could do things like be smart

204
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:13,200
 and leave some value in a register

205
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:15,760
 and then check the register a couple of different ways,

206
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:19,440
 and that would lead to really succinct, fast code.

207
00:09:19,440 --> 00:09:22,620
 Hand-tuned code where you might have to look at it

208
00:09:22,620 --> 00:09:23,760
 to figure out what it's doing,

209
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:26,780
 but then you realize, well, I did that in six statements

210
00:09:26,780 --> 00:09:28,140
 rather than 12 statements.

211
00:09:28,140 --> 00:09:29,500
 12 statements might have made more sense,

212
00:09:29,500 --> 00:09:32,200
 but the six statements were really fast.

213
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:34,360
 And in the early days, in the early '70s,

214
00:09:34,360 --> 00:09:36,960
 they were changing their compilers so fast

215
00:09:36,960 --> 00:09:39,220
 and changing their hardware so fast

216
00:09:39,220 --> 00:09:41,320
 that they really didn't build

217
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,600
 super great optimizing compilers.

218
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:45,560
 So they would look at the source code

219
00:09:45,560 --> 00:09:46,800
 that came out of the compiler

220
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:48,400
 and they're like, I could do better than that.

221
00:09:48,400 --> 00:09:50,920
 So there was a lot of a kind of comparison

222
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:55,920
 of the source code between what the C compiler would generate

223
00:09:55,920 --> 00:09:58,600
 and whatever, and so they found over time

224
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:01,800
 that if they would kind of use these tricks

225
00:10:01,800 --> 00:10:06,680
 that told the compiler to take this C equals getchar

226
00:10:06,680 --> 00:10:11,680
 and leave the C in a register and compare it to a space,

227
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:14,200
 and then compare it again to a new line

228
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:16,440
 and compare it again to a tab, we would think,

229
00:10:16,440 --> 00:10:19,000
 oh, I can see how that would run in assembly language.

230
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,340
 And I can hope that the compiler

231
00:10:21,340 --> 00:10:23,340
 would generate the assembly language

232
00:10:23,340 --> 00:10:28,340
 that would make me happy.

233
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:30,440
 And then another pattern you see in this

234
00:10:30,440 --> 00:10:33,120
 is the number four thing where all the work's been done

235
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:36,040
 in the loop test, and so while loop,

236
00:10:36,040 --> 00:10:38,320
 that whole big expression is just the test

237
00:10:38,320 --> 00:10:41,220
 to know when it's done, but it's actually reading the data,

238
00:10:41,220 --> 00:10:44,760
 comparing it three times, storing it in a variable,

239
00:10:44,760 --> 00:10:47,520
 and when that's all done, there's nothing to do in the loop,

240
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:50,640
 and so that's why you say close paren semicolon.

241
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:52,400
 And you'll see a lot of those things,

242
00:10:52,400 --> 00:10:53,900
 especially when doing string stuff

243
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:55,720
 where you're sort of zooming through an array

244
00:10:55,720 --> 00:10:57,480
 and you did it all in the for loop

245
00:10:57,480 --> 00:10:59,720
 and you don't really have anything to do in the for loop.

246
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:03,320
 And again, we're thinking in the early days

247
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:05,640
 of how this is gonna translate into assembly language,

248
00:11:05,640 --> 00:11:08,000
 and so you're trying to make that loop really, really small.

249
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,680
 And again, it's amazing how often they looked

250
00:11:10,680 --> 00:11:13,280
 at the resulting assembly language

251
00:11:13,280 --> 00:11:15,400
 in a non-optimizing compiler situation

252
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:18,080
 and then wondered if the compiler could have done better.

253
00:11:18,080 --> 00:11:21,880
 So that gets us going in this chapter.

254
00:11:21,880 --> 00:11:23,160
 We talked about the semicolon,

255
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:24,920
 we talked about the switch statement,

256
00:11:24,920 --> 00:11:29,200
 the else if, subtle syntax difference between Python and C,

257
00:11:29,200 --> 00:11:32,080
 the comma, and just get used to the notion

258
00:11:32,080 --> 00:11:33,640
 that it's obtuse code.

259
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:35,400
